          </subsection>
          
          <subsection>
            <title>Logical Equivalence</title>
            
            
            
            <p>
              A fundamental skill in analyzing and proving mathematical statements is the ability to carefully describe their logical structure and, when appropriate, convert the statement into a <term>logically equivalent</term> statement.
              Ideally, the new equivalent form of the statement will have a structure more amenable to a particular type of proof or solution.
            </p>
            
            <definition>
              <index>logical equivalence</index>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Two statements <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> are said to be <term>logically equivalent</term> if they have the same truth table.
                  In this case, we write <m>P \equiv Q</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>
            
            <exploration>
              <index>double negation</index>
              <title>Double Negation</title>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Use a truth table to verify that <m>P\equiv \neg (\neg P)</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </exploration>
            
            
            <exploration>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Use a truth table to determine whether the following statements are logically equivalent.
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li><m>P\Leftrightarrow Q</m></li>
                  <li><m>(P\Rightarrow Q)\land (Q\Rightarrow P)</m></li>
                </ul>
              </statement>
            </exploration>
            
            
            <p>
              Given an implication <m>P\Rightarrow Q</m>, one may construct some related statements.
            </p>
            
            <definition>
              <index>converse</index>
              <index>contrapositive</index>
              <index>inverse</index>
              <index><h>implication</h><h>converse of</h></index>
              <index><h>implication</h><h>contrapositive of</h></index>
              <index><h>implication</h><h>inverse of</h></index>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> be statements.
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li>The <term>converse of the statement <m>P\Rightarrow Q</m></term> is the statement <m>Q\Rightarrow P</m>.</li>
                  <li>The <term>contrapositive of the statement <m>P\Rightarrow Q</m></term> is the statement <m>(\neg Q)\Rightarrow (\neg P)</m>.</li>
                  <li>Thhe <term>inverse of the statement <m>P\Rightarrow Q</m></term> is the statement <m>(\neg P)\Rightarrow (\neg Q)</m>.</li>
                </ul>
              </statement>
            </definition>
            
            
            <activity>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Choose at least two conditional statements we've mentioned in class and state the coverse, contrapositive, and inverse of each.
                  Based on the statements you wrote, make a conjecture<fn>A conjecture is a precise educated <q>guess</q> about what is true in general.</fn> about how the truth values of these four implications (the original conditional statement, together with its converse, contrapositive, and inverse) seem to relate.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </activity>
            
            <exploration>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Use truth tables to identify any logical equivalences between <m>P\Rightarrow Q</m>, <m>Q\rightarrow P</m>, <m>(\neg Q)\Rightarrow (\neg P)</m>, and <m>(\neg P)\Rightarrow (\neg Q)</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </exploration>
            
            <exploration xml:id="prob-le-contradiction">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Show that <m>P\rightarrow Q \equiv (\neg P) \lor Q</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </exploration>
            
            <p>
              The following pairs of logical equivalences, named for British mathematician <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Augustus_De_Morgan">Augustus De Morgan</url>, allow us to convert conjunctions to disjunctions, and vice versa.
            </p>
            
            <exploration xml:id="prob-demorgan-stmt">
              <index>De Morgan's Laws (for statements)</index>
              <title>De Morgan's Laws</title>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Show that the following pairs of statements are logically equivalent.
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li><m>\neg (P\land Q)</m> and <m>(\neg P) \lor (\neg Q)</m></li>
                  <li><m>\neg (P\lor Q)</m> and <m>(\neg P)\land (\neg Q)</m></li>
                </ul>
              </statement>
            </exploration>
            
            <exploration xml:id="prob-distlaws-stmt">
              <index>distributive laws (for statements)</index>
              <title>Distributive Laws</title>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>P, Q, R</m> be statements.
                  Use truth tables to verify the following equivalences, but be careful<mdash />how many rows should your truth table contain?
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li><m>P\land (Q\lor R) \equiv P\lor (Q\land R)</m></li>
                  <li><m>P\lor (Q\land R) \equiv P \land (Q\lor R)</m></li>
                </ul>
              </statement>
            </exploration>
                  
                  
            <p>
              We will often interested in proving conditional statements in which our antecdents or consequents have multiple cases.
              The following equivalences will come in handy.
            </p>
            
            <exploration>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Use truth tables to verify the following.
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li><m>P\Rightarrow (Q\land R) \equiv (P\land \neg Q)\Rightarrow R</m></li>
                  <li><m>(P\lor Q)\Rightarrow R \equiv (P\Rightarrow R)\land (Q\Rightarrow R)</m></li>
                </ul>
              </statement>
            </exploration>
                  
            <p>
              To conclude this section, we mention two types of special statements: tautologies and contradictions.
            </p>
            
            <definition>
              <index>tautology</index>
              <index>contradiction</index>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  A statement is called a <term>tautology</term> if it is always true.
                  A statement is called a <term>contradiction</term> if it is never true.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>
            
            <figure xml:id="fig-tautology-club">
              <image xml:id="img-tautology-club" source="https://imgs.xkcd.com/comics/honor_societies.png" width="75%" />
              <caption>
              From <url href="https://xkcd.com/703/">XKCD 703: Honor Societies</url>
              </caption>
            </figure>
            
            <activity>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> be statements.
                  Determine, with proof, whether the following are tautologies, contradictions, or neither.
                </p>
                <ol>
                  <li><m>P\land (\neg P)</m></li>
                  <li><m>P\lor (\neg P)</m></li>
                  <li><m>P\Rightarrow (P\Rightarrow (P\Rightarrow (P\Rightarrow Q)))</m></li>
                  <li><m>P\Rightarrow (\neg P\Rightarrow (P\Rightarrow (\neg P\Rightarrow Q)))</m></li>
                </ol>
              </statement>
            </activity>
            
            
            
            
            
            
          </subsection>
          
